Dissertation Submitted to Hangzhou Dianzi University
for the Degree of Master
Research on Decoding Methods of
Unilateral Limb Motor Imagery Based
on EEG-EMG Fusion
Candidate: Zhang JiaZheng
Supervisor: Assoc. Prof. Yang Bing
Prof. Kong Wanzeng
May, 2025


杭州电子科技大学硕士学位论文
I
摘要
本文旨在开发一种基于脑肌电多模态融合深度解码的康复手套系统,用于脑
卒中患者上肢运动功能障碍的主动康复训练。传统的运动想象分类算法在左右手
分类任务中表现出较高的准确性,广泛应用于二分类场景。然而,当面对更加精
细的单侧手势识别任务时,传统方法由于缺乏神经先验机制,难以挖掘其潜在特
征信息,从而导致分类性能受限。因此,如何提升单侧肢体运动意图识别的准确
性成为当前研究的重要挑战。针对这个问题,本研究结合脑电信号(EEG)和肌
电信号(EMG),通过多模态数据融合提升单侧肢体运动意图识别的准确性,从
而为卒中患者的康复提供精准且个性化的解决方案。以下是本研究的主要内容和
创新成果:
(1)针对多模态时序信号的有效融合问题,本文提出了一种基于注意力机
制的脑 肌电 融合 单 侧 肢体运 动想 象解码 方 法 (Fusion-modal-feature-learning,
FMFL)。该算法提取脑电的 FBCSP 特征和肌电的时域统计特征,并通过注意力
机制动态分配脑电和肌电特征的权重,从而有效缓解了跨模态特征显著性差异缺
失的问题。实验结果表明,在 MSD-11M 数据集和 EEG-EMG-Gesture 数据集上,
FMFL 相比特征拼接显著提升了分类准确率,验证了注意力机制在多模态特征融
合中的关键作用。
(2)进一步针对手动提取特征难以充分挖掘脑肌电信号互补性的问题,本
文提出了一种基于动态门控融合策略的多模态特征交互学习模型(Inter-modal
feature-learning, IMFL)。该模型通过深度学习自动提取 EEG 的时空特征和 EMG
的时序依赖关系,并利用双向动态门控网络实现多模态特征交互。实验结果表明,
在单侧手势识别任务中,尤其是在多类别复杂分类任务中表现突出。在消融实验
中,IMFL 模型在大部分情况下优于其他消融模型,并且各任务的准确率都有显
著提升。表明其能够充分挖掘不同模态间的互补关系,提取具有更高判别性的多
模态交互特征。
(3)基于研究内容(1)和(2)的成果,本文进一步设计开发了一套面向
上肢功能障碍患者的脑肌电融合康复手套系统。该系统由脑肌电数据采集模块、
信号处理模块、模型训练模块以及康复手套硬件模块组成。其中,脑肌电数据采
集模块负责实时采集患者的脑电和肌电信号;信号处理模块负责数据传输和预处
理;模型训练模块会用预处理后的数据训练模型,用于后续的康复训练。康复手
套硬件模块通过单片机控制气泵和气阀的开关,驱动气动柔性手套辅助患者完成


杭州电子科技大学硕士学位论文
II
抓握和伸展动作。该系统具有良好的可靠性,能够有效降低患者在康复训练中的
受伤风险,同时提升了系统的实用性和用户体验。此外,通过融合多模态生理信
号,该系统显著增强了对患者运动意图的解码能力,为卒中患者的个性化康复训
练提供了新的技术支持。
关键词:运动想象,脑电信号,肌电信号,特征交互,康复手套


杭州电子科技大学硕士学位论文
III
ABSTRACT
This thesis aims to develop a rehabilitation glove system based on deep decoding
of electroencephalogram (EEG) and electromyography (EMG) multimodal fusion for
active rehabilitation training of stroke patients with upper-limb motor dysfunction.
Traditional motor imagery classification algorithms exhibit high accuracy in left-right
hand classification tasks and are widely applied to binary classification scenarios.
However, when facing more refined unilateral gesture recognition tasks, conventional
methods struggle to extract latent feature information due to the lack of neural prior
mechanisms, resulting in limited classification performance. Consequently, improving
the accuracy of unilateral limb motion intention recognition has become a critical
research challenge. To address this issue, this research integrates EEG and EMG signals
to enhance the accuracy of unilateral limb motion intention recognition through
multimodal data fusion, thereby providing precise and personalized rehabilitation
solutions for stroke patients. The main contributions and innovations of this study are
as follows:
(1) To resolve the effective fusion of temporal multimodal signals, this paper
proposes a unilateral limb motor imagery decoding method based on attention-guided
EEG-EMG fusion (Fusion-Modal-Feature-Learning, FMFL). This algorithm extracts
EEG features using Filter Bank Common Spatial Pattern (FBCSP) and EMG time
domain statistical features, dynamically assigning weights to EEG and EMG features
via an attention mechanism. This approach effectively alleviates the issue of missing
cross-modal feature saliency differences. Experimental results on the MSD-11M and
EEG-EMG-Gesture datasets demonstrate that FMFL significantly improves
classification accuracy compared to simple feature concatenation, validating the critical
role of attention mechanisms in multimodal feature fusion.
(2) To further address the insufficient exploitation of EEG-EMG complementarity
through manual feature extraction, this study proposes a multimodal feature interaction
learning model based on a dynamic gated fusion strategy (Inter-Modal-Feature
Learning, IMFL). The model automatically extracts spatiotemporal features from EEG
and temporal dependencies from EMG via deep learning, and implements multimodal
feature interaction using a bidirectional dynamic gated network. Experimental results


杭州电子科技大学硕士学位论文
IV
highlight its superior performance in unilateral gesture recognition tasks, particularly
in multi-class complex classification scenarios. Ablation studies confirm that the IMFL
model outperforms other variants across most tasks, with significant accuracy
improvements, indicating its capability to fully exploit inter-modal complementarity
and extract discriminative interactive features.
(3) Building on the achievements of (1) and (2), this study further designs and
develops an EEG-EMG fusion rehabilitation glove system for patients with upper-limb
dysfunction. The system comprises four modules: EEG-EMG data acquisition, signal
processing, model training, and rehabilitation glove hardware. The acquisition module
collects real-time EEG and EMG signals from patients; the signal processing module
handles data transmission and preprocessing; the model training module trains the
algorithm using preprocessed data for subsequent rehabilitation. The hardware module
employs a microcontroller to control air pumps and solenoid valves, driving a
pneumatic soft glove to assist patients in performing grasping and extension motions.
The system demonstrates high reliability, effectively reducing injury risks during
rehabilitation training while enhancing practicality and user experience. By integrating
multimodal physiological signals, the system significantly improves motion intention
decoding accuracy, offering novel technical support for personalized rehabilitation
training in stroke patients.
Keywords: motor imagery, electroencephalogram (EEG), electromyography (EMG),
feature interaction, rehabilitation glove


